  "62": {
    "John Trapp": "And ye shall be left few in number. ] And so \"shall know my breach of covenant,\" because ye broke first.\nVer.\n62. And ye shall be left few in number.] And so \"shall know my breach of covenant,\" because ye broke first.\nVer.",
    "Mark Allan Powell, Mark E. Biddle, Martin Luther": "(\u201clike the\nstars of the heavens\u201d) suggest that the author was familiar with\nthe written patriarchal tradition.\n(4) The reference to \u201cthe land where you are\u201d (\nv. 62). YHWH, who had hoped to make Israel number \u201cas\nthe stars of the heavens (\nv. 62),\u201d who had rejoiced in doing Israel\ngood and blessing it, will take delight in \u201cannihilating (<bd),\u201d\n\u201cdestroying (\u00a1md),\u201d and \u201ctearing away (nsh).\u201d The words of the\nbook of the Torah hold the key to Israel\u2019s very survival!\nThe second and final subsection elucidates the idea that YHWH\nwill \u201ctear [Israel] away from the land.\u201d Again, in a very logical and\nlinear progression, this unit outlines Israel\u2019s experience of exile.\nFirst, the text declares that Israel will be scattered among nations to\nthe far reaches of the world, \u201cthere to serve other gods, previously\nunknown to you or your fathers, gods of wood and stone\u201d ("
  },
  "63": {
    "John Trapp": "So the Lord will rejoice over you. ] See here the venomous nature of sin, so far forth offensive to Almighty God, as to cause him, who otherwise afflicts not willingly, { #La 3:33 } but delights in mercy, { #Mic 7:18 } to rejoice in the ruin of his creatures, as here, to laugh at their destruction, and mock when their fear cometh, { #Pr 1:26 } to take as much pleasure therein as a man would do in a cup of generous wine, { #Re 16:19 } and to be as much eased thereby, as one over-gorged would be in ridding his stomach of that which oppressed it. { #Re 3:16 }\nVer.\n63. So the Lord will rejoice over you.] See here the venomous nature of sin, so far forth offensive to Almighty God, as [v_Lam_3_33] to cause him, who otherwise afflicts not willingly, {#La 3:33} but [v_Mic_7_18] delights in mercy, {#Mic 7:18} to rejoice in the ruin of his creatures, as here, to laugh at their destruction, and mock when their fear [v_Pro_1_26] cometh, {#Pr 1:26} to take as much pleasure therein as a man would [v_Rev_16_19] do in a cup of generous wine, {#Re 16:19} and to be as much eased thereby, as one over-gorged would be in ridding his stomach of that [v_Rev_3_16] which oppressed it. {#Re 3:16}\nVer.",
    "Mark Allan Powell, Mark E. Biddle, Martin Luther": ") contrasts with\nthe typical Deuteronomic expressions, \u201cthe land to which you\nare going,\u201d \u201cthe land you are going to possess,\u201d and \u201cthe land\nYHWH is giving you.\u201d It suggests that, from the perspective of\nthe author of this addendum, possession of the land is an estab-\nlished fact. In other words, like the references to \u201cthe book,\u201d\nthis expression makes no effort to maintain the perspective of\nMoses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`\u2019 address in Moab.\nAs indicated above, the unit, which is unified by the ominous\nspecter of Egyptian bondage (vv. 60, 68), divides neatly into two\nsubsections governed by the shift in focus from the contents of the\nbook in vv. 58-63 to dispersion among the nations in vv. 64-"
  },
